Introduction

In today’s modern of age of intense international competition, our group wanted to better understand how national expenditure on education affected international university rankings, if at all. To that end, we found data sets that gave us international university rankings, as well as a data set that gave us national expenditure on education in 36 different countries.

After much analysis, we conclude that national expenditure on education is not a conclusive predictor of that country’s average university world ranking. In technical terms, we do not have sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis that a country’s average university world ranking is not determined at all by that country’s expenditure on higher education.

Background

The Data

Our team began by searching Kaggle.com for data on international university rankings and national expenditure on education. On Kaggle, we found Myles O’Neill’s repository of World University Rankings data.1 From this repository, we used three data sets.

University Ranking Data Sets

For the first of these datasets, we used the Center for World University Rankings (CWUR) data. There is information for the years 2012, 2013, 2014, and 2015. In 2014 and 2015, 1,000 Universities were ranked, unlike the previous two years that ranked the top 100 Universities instead. The data contains information such as the rank of the institution, name, country, rank within the country, etc. Next, we have a dataset from the Academic Ranking of World Universities (ARWU), in which the ShanghaiRanking Consultancy gives their own list of University rankings. The data includes information from the year 2005 to 2015. The dataset contains the world rank of the institution, name, rank within country, ‘score’ of University, etc. Our last dataset was obtained from Times Higher Education World University Ranking (Times Ranking). The data includes information from 2011 through 2016. Unlike the ShanghaiRanking, Times Ranking allows the possibility of ‘tying’, where a University’s rank can be shared with another University, but only occurs outside of the top 100 Universities ranked. The data includes the same information as the previous dataset, but includes scores that are broken down; such as an international score, research score, citation score, income score, and total score. Not all countries are in each dataset, as it depends on the institution that created the ranking.

Expenditure Data

We used two additional data sets for our analysis. Borrowing from the work O’Neill had already done, we sought out the root of the expenditure data he had found. This data came from the United States’ National Center for Education Statistics’ 2014 Digest of Education Statistics.2 It includes data for each of the 34 countries that were in the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) in 2014, as well as data from Brazil and the Russian Federation. To this, we also added data from the 2019 Digest of Education Statistics. Each of these included data from 3 years ago (2011 and 2016 data respectively), with expenditure measured as a percentage of the country’s Gross Domestic Product (GDP). We pulled out this 2011 and 2016 spending data for each country in the OECD.

Preparing The Data

The first step with our data was to clean and prepare it for analysis.

As mentioned above, we decided to only consider national spending on higher education in 2011 and 2016. These are the years we found spending data to be the most recent and complete from the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).

Regarding the three different ranking systems, our goal was to combine them in some way, so that any biases in the rankings could be averaged out. To that end, we decided on a three step process for merging the rankings:

  1. Group each university by the country it is in.

  2. Find the average ranking for each country in each data set.

  3. Find the average country ranking between the three data sets.

We decided on this process because there were too many semantic differences in the university names between the three rankings (for example, the CWUR and Times data refer to our school as “University of Wisconsin-Madison”, while the Shanghai data refer to “University of Wiscosin - Madison”. Since the spacing is different, the terms would not match). Without manually ensuring each school was listed the same in each data set, we could not ensure each university matched. However, the country names were easy to confirm as exactly the same between data sets. Thus, by finding the average rank of each country per data set, we could avoid the issue of university names not matching between data sets.

It is also important to note that we decided to focus our attention on the top 100 universities from each ranking system for each year in which data was provided, and no universities below the top 100. The reason for this is that each ranking organization treated institutions below the top 100 differently (the CWUR data ranked the top 1000 universities, while the Shanghai data gave a range of rankings for those ranked below 100, and the Times data allowed for tied scores below the 100 ranking). In order to avoid any errors that might arise from these incongruities, we selected only the top 100 universities from each data set.

A final note regarding the cleaning of our data is that the Shanghai data set did not include a column for the university’s country. However, with us only considering the top 100 institutions from that data set, it was more reasonable for us to add this column to the data set manually. We did so by pulling university and country pairs from the CWUR data (as the largest data set, it had the most pairs), and matching university names with the Shanghai data. While there were a number of semantic disagreements between the two data sets, we manually overcame them and moved forward.

Having cut the data from each ranking agency down to their top 100 universities in each year for which data was available, and found each country’s average rank, we merged this data together using country and year as a key and found the average world ranking of each country’s institutions throughout all the years for which ranking data was included.

We then filtered out countries from this data that were not members of the OECD (as we only had data on OECD member countries), and adjoined to this remaining list the education spending of each country in 2011 and 2016.

We now had a data table from which we could properly do analysis. The first ten rows of this table are included to further elucidate understanding of our methods:

Our table has a column with the country name, a column that pairs each country with a year in which the average world rank was calculated, a column for the average world rank for that year, a column for the percentage of GDP spent by each country in 2011 on higher education, and a column for the percentage of GDP spent by each country in 2016 on higher education.

“NA” values represent years in which spending data was not available due to the country not being a current member of the OECD.

We had one final question from our data: what if there was a delayed effect? That is, what if spending in 2011 had a correlation with a rank improvement in a year later than 2011 that was stronger than the correlation within that same year? Was there any evidence of a delayed correlation, of spending in 2011 really making a difference in another year? We took a look:

This graph compares each country’s 2011 higher education expenditure amount (as a percentage of GDP) to its average university ranking for each year from 2012 to 2015 (further discussion of the regression occurs in the Discussion section).

With our graphical analysis concluded, we needed to see just how strong any correlations were. Using least mean squares analysis, we calculated the estimate of the slope for each of the above graphs, as well as a p-value for that estimate. We put these values into the following table:

Discussion

From our analysis, we conclude that national expenditure on education is not a conclusive predictor of that country’s average university world ranking.

We make this conclusion based on the relatively large p-scores for the LMS analysis of average world ranking against expenditure in each year from 2011 to 2016. The only year in which 2011 expenditure is a statistically significant predictor of average world ranking is 2016, and even then it is barely significant at the 0.1 level.

This does bring up an interesting question, however: if 2011 expenditure only results in a statistically significant effect on average world ranking in 2016, does this mean we should expect all expenditure effects to be delayed? In other words, does expenditure on education in a year only create dividends five years later? Answering this question may be a task for future study, and future data.

In order to further confirm our assessment that expenditure is not a conclusive predictor of institutional excellence, we compared expenditure to another metric common to each data set: institutional score. This average score, with a maximum value of 100, might be another way to examine how expenditure affects university success.

In this analysis, expenditure was a statistically significant predictor of average score in several years, but never at more than the 0.05 level. Interestingly, 2011 expenditure was most significant at affecting score in 2014. This lends some additional credence to the idea that the effects of expenditure are delayed, and not in the year immediately following the spending.

While we trust in our analysis, we do recognize there are a number of areas for improvement, and also that some of our assumptions may be faulty. It is important to note from the beginning that no data source is ever perfectly clean, or composed of all the data we might like to have. The lack of data for national expenditure on private institutions over the years constrained us greatly in our work. Additionally, since we only had expenditure datas for certain countries, other countries with exceptional universities were left out of our analysis, such as China and India. As far as our assumptions are concerned, averaging the rankings between three organizations may have some inherent flaws to it, since each organization uses different criteria to create their rankings. Some of this could be overcome by comparing expenditure to each criteria, and seeing which of those criteria is most or least affected by expenditure. This is yet another avenue for further study.

In conclusion, there is much to be learned about how expenditure affects worldwide university rankings, but we feel confident in saying that expenditure is not the most conclusive predictor of an educational institutions success.
